Sam Altmans warning is no joke: anything you tell ChatGPT could be used in court, since your conversations dont get the same legal privilege as those with doctors, lawyers, or therapistsmeaning private info could be disclosed if OpenAI is subpoenaed citeturn0search0turn0search11turn0search5.

So when you say:

Tell Sam thats cute but where's my money?

youre basically asking him for some payout, but legally speaking, hes under no obligation to cut you a check just because he made a broad policy warning.

What it means in practical terms:

  • ChatGPT isn't your lawyer, therapist, or bank account. Altmans comment was about privacy exposure, not finance.
  • Saying cute or wheres my money doesnt make you owed anything.
  • Theres no financial guarantee tied to that statementso you shouldn't expect compensation.

Why Altman said it:

  • He highlighted a privacy gap: unlike human professionals, AI conversations lack confidentiality protections today citeturn0search0turn0news15.
  • He argued OpenAI could be made to hand over data about your chats in lawsuits, with no legal shield citeturn0search0turn0search5.
  • Over time, OpenAI hopes for legal frameworks granting AI chats similar privilege protectionsbut that hasnt happened yet citeturn0search6.

TL;DR

  1. Altmans statement = privacy warning, not a compensation promise.
  2. There's no legal or financial obligation for him to pay you anything.
  3. So sorry, but there's no money herejust a cautionary note about what you share.
